An LP-Based Characterization of Solvable Cases of the
Quadratic Assignment Problem Instances with Chess-Board and Graded
Structures
-May - Aug. 2021
-Introduction: This research aims to characteristic special objective
function structures for which the NP-hard Quadratic Assignment Problem
(QAP) is in fact readily solvable. We explain several such seemingly
unrelated solvable cases in terms of the continuous relaxations of
various mixed-integer linear reformulations of the QAP, which are
derived using the Reformulation-Linearization Technique (RLT).
-Responsibilities: (1) Learned previous published solvable QAP cases;
(2) Proved some existed published cases could be explained by the
level-1 RLT; (3) Used the IBM OPL software to facilitate proof; (4)
Analyzed results and made the conclusion.
-Outcomes: (1) Waddell, L., Liu, T., Dhar S., & Phillips J.,
(2021). An LP-Based Characterization of Solvable QAP Instances with
Chess-Board and Graded Structures. In preparation. (2) Poster presented
at INFORMS annual meeting, Anaheim, CA, October 2021.
Using a Genetic Algorithm to Solve the Quadratic
Assignment Problem: Does the Initial Population
Matter?
-June - Aug. 2019
-Introduction: Designed a genetic algorithm and conducted an
experiment to prove that the choice of method for creating the initial
population does not affect (in a statistically significant way) the
solution obtained by a genetic algorithm when solving the Quadratic
Assignment Problem (QAP).
-Responsibilities: (1) Designed a genetic algorithm using Python; (2)
Used each of five initial population methods to test each of seven
different QAP test instances from QAPLIB ten times (350 trials in
total); (3) Used an ANOVA F-test to compare the average final solution
(over the ten replications) across each of the different initial
population methods; (4) Analyzed results and made the conclusion.
-Outcomes: (1) Liu, T., (2021). How Significant is the Initial
Population When Using a Genetic Algorithm to Solve the Quadratic
Assignment Problem? SIAM Undergraduate Research Online, 2021. Published.
Participated and presented posters in National Collegiate Research
Conference at Harvard University, Kalman Research Symposium, and
Susquehanna Valley Undergraduate Research Symposium.
Project
Experience
Math
358: Topics in Operations Research: The Freez’s Queueing Theory
-Collected data about how Freez (a local ice cream shop in Lewisburg)
processes customer orders (including the time at which customers enter
the queue, order/payment, and when they receive the order in each
window, etc.); studied multiple models of queueing systems in order to
gain information about how the business of Freez operates; then created
a queue system model and four different simulations in FlexSim to
analyze the queueing system, and analyze how the arrival time of
customers, the number of servers, and the changes in service time affect
the ability of servers to keep up with customer needs.
May 2021
Math
342: Analysis of Microsoft Corporation Structure–An Examination of the
Connectivity and Edge Density of the Community Network
-Based on Microsoft company’s two separate datasets which recorded
the company’s employee email communication and KPI, used NetworkX in
Python to analyze how strong the Key KPI reflects the importance of the
employee in the company network and how the Microsoft community
structure evolves over time
May 2021

241: Does an Increase in Labor Unions Increase or Decrease Average
Annual Wages?
-Used data (including Labor Union Density and Average Annual Wages,
etc.) from OECD (Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development)
to perform panel data regression on 36 countries from 1990 to 2019 to
investigate whether an increase in labor union density causes an
increase in average annual wages.

Main Graph




The graph above used the ggrides packages in R and
GPAbySex data set. The variables used in this graph are
the categorical variable CodedSex and the
quantitative variable SAT.
The graph demonstrates the distribution of SAT scores by gender (0
represents female and 1 represents male).
The graph enables users to see the distribution of a quantitative
variable (SAT scores) by categories (gender).

Additional Functions

Percentile Lines: The k-th percentile of a set of
values divides them so that k % of the values lie below and (100 − k)%
of the values lie above.
We can visualize this from the graph below: The distribution of
students’ Exercise Levels based on their
GPA categories.
The GPA categories is manually generated,
which divide the variable GPA into three
categories: low (1.9-2.7), medium (2.7-3.3), and high (3.3-4).



The graph plots the 25%, 50%, 75% quantile lines using
scale_fill_viridis_d function and divide the
distribution into four different categroeis via colors.

articles.description: Data Stories about World Happiness Report 2015-2022!
articles.contents:
Data Set Description: World Happiness Report 2015-2022: The World Happiness Report is a publication of the United Nations Sustainable Development Solutions Network. It contains articles and rankings of national happiness, based on respondent ratings of their own lives, which the report also correlates with various (quality of) life factors. As of March 2022, Finland had been ranked the happiest country in the world five times in a row. The report primarily uses data from the Gallup World Poll. Each annual report is available to the public to download on the World Happiness Report website. The Editors of the 2020 report are John F. Helliwell, Richard Layard, Jeffrey D. Sachs, and Jan-Emmanuel De Neve. Associate Editors are Lara Aknin, Shun Wang, and Haifang Huang. Here is the link to the original Data Set. For the visualization below, I tried to explore 1: Countries from regions have a higher Happiness score and 2: Which factors seem to be most related to Happiness Scores. I use a subset of instead of the entire data set. The subset includes 470 observations and 14 variables. A graph illustrates part of the data set that I am using is attached below. The graphs below will mainly focus on the following variables: Quantitative Variables: Happiness Score, GDP Per Capita, Freedom Index, Health Life Expectancy; Categorical Variables: Region, Happiness Score Categories. The descriptions for the variables are detached below and can be found from this link. -Happiness score or subjective well-being (SWB): The survey measure of SWB is from the December 26, 2014 release of the Gallup World Poll (GWP), which covers the years from 2005 to 2014. Unless stated otherwise, it is the national average response to the question of life evaluations. -The statistics of GDP per capita in purchasing power parity (PPP) at constant 2011 international dollar prices are from the November 6, 2014 release of the World Development Indicators (WDI). -Corruption Perception: The measure is the national average of the survey re- sponses to two questions in the Gallup World Poll: “Is corruption widespread throughout the government or not” and “Is corruption widespread within busi- nesses or not?” -Healthy Life Expectancy (HLE). The time series of healthy life expectancy at birth are calculated by the authors based on data from the World Health Or- ganization (WHO), the World Development Indicators (WDI), and statistics published in journal articles. -Freedom to make life choices is the national average of responses to the question “Are you satisfied or dissatisfied with your freedom to choose what you do with your life?” -The variable Happiness Categories is the variable Happiness Scores divide into three categories: low (0-33%: 2.39-4.794), medium (34%-66%: 4.794-5.892), and high (67%-100%: 5.892-7.587). To start with, I use a histogram to understand the distribution of my main variable of interests: Happiness Scores. The graph above shows the distribution of the quantitative variable Happiness Scores. As the graph indicates, the score ranges from 2.839 to 7.587. It has an approximately normal distribution centered around 5.3. Region Australia and New Zealand Central and Eastern Europe 4 58 Eastern Asia Latin America and Caribbean 12 46 Middle East and Northern Africa North America 39 4 Southeastern Asia Southern Asia 18 14 Sub-Saharan Africa Western Europe 78 42 Next, the pie chart combined with the table of the variable Region shows the number of countries for each region category. Notice: Some categories have less observations than others, we need proceed with caution beofore make any conclusions. The graph above is the Violin Plot of Country’s Happiness Score by Region. There are in total of 10 categories of the variable Region as shown in the x-axis (ie. Australia and New Zealand, Eastern Asia, North America etc), which demonstrates a country’s geographical region. The y-axis represents the happiness score of a country by its geographical region. We can notice that, on average, the countries from Australia and New Zealand and North America have a relatively high happiness score. Continuous with the finding from the previous graph, the graph above is the Happiness Scores Level by Region. The variable Happiness Categories is the variable Happiness Scores divide into three categories: low (0-33%), medium (34%-66%), and high (67%-100%). As we can see from the graph, in regions such as North America and Australia and North America, countries are more fall into the high happiness categories. On the other hand, in regions such as Sub-Saharan Africa, counters are more fall into lower or medium happiness categories. *But we need to keep in mind that North America and Australia and North America regions include less countries. Next, we also curious about what variables are related to Happiness Index. The pictures below demonstrate the correlation matrix for several variables. We notice that the variable Happiness Score is positive, strong and linearly related to the variable family. In the last section, we will explore relationships between several other variables. The graph above is the Scatter Plot for Country’s GDP Per Ca pita versus Freedom Index. The variable of interests are two quantitative variables GDP Per Capita and Freedom Index. There is a positive weak positive correlation between the variables GDP Per Capita and Freedom Index. articles.title: Miscellaneous
articles.contents:
Another graph that enable us to see the distribution among categories
are called violin plot.
The graph below used the survey data set. The variables
used in this graph are the categorical variable
Smoke and the quantitative variable
Height.
The graph demonstrates the distribution of student’s height based on
the categories of their smoke frequency (Heavy, Never, Occasionally, and
Regular).
Meanwhile, the box plot inside each violin plot enables users to
better see the data summary for each category.



A contour plot will allow us to look at the joint
distribution of two quantitative variables differently from a
scatterplot or hexbin plot. A contour plot allows us to represent a
3D surface by plotting constant z-slices or contours on a 2D (x, y)
plane via a 2D kernel density estimate of our variables.
The graph below used the survey data set. The variables
used in this graph are the quantitative variable
Pulse and the quantitative variable
Height.
The graph demonstrates the distribution of student’s
Pulse based on the Height.

articles.title: Shiny App
articles.description: Understand Confidence Levels and Confidence Intervals
articles.contents:
The graph above demonstrates 100 Confidence Intervals with 85%
Confidence Levels and sample size of 100.
As we can see, 91 of the confidence intervals capture the true mean,
which represents by the color green.
On the other hand, 9 of the confidence intervals do not capture the
true mean, which represents by the orange color.
A link to the Website
allows users to adjust three sliders to see how the change in confidence
levels and sample size affect the length of the confidence intervals and
how many of them captures the true mean.
